{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "SI Units",
      "simpleDefinition": "The international standard system of measurement used to ensure technical consistency across the world.",
      "anchor": "The universal 'rulebook' for measurements so every electrician speaks the same language.",
      "misconception": "Thinking that electrical units change depending on the country; they are globally standardized."
    },
    {
      "term": "Base Units",
      "simpleDefinition": "Fundamental measurements that are not derived from any other unit, such as length (m) and mass (kg).",
      "anchor": "The basic building blocks of all measurement.",
      "misconception": "Thinking area or volume are base units; they are actually built from length."
    },
    {
      "term": "Derived Units",
      "simpleDefinition": "Units created by combining base units, such as velocity (m/s) or area (m²).",
      "anchor": "A 'recipe' of base units mixed together to measure something more complex.",
      "misconception": "Believing all units are independent; most are combinations of the core base units."
    },
    {
      "term": "Quantity vs Unit",
      "simpleDefinition": "The 'Quantity' is the physical property being measured; the 'Unit' is the standard used to measure it.",
      "anchor": "Quantity is the 'What' (e.g., Current), Unit is the 'How much' (e.g., Amperes).",
      "misconception": "Using the unit name (like 'Volts') to describe the quantity (which is 'Voltage')."
    },
    {
      "term": "Resistance",
      "simpleDefinition": "The opposition to the flow of electric current, measured in Ohms (Ω).",
      "anchor": "Like a narrow section in a pipe that slows down water flow.",
      "misconception": "Confusing Resistance (the circuit's opposition) with Resistivity (the material's specific property)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Power",
      "simpleDefinition": "The rate at which electrical energy is transferred or used, measured in Watts (W).",
      "anchor": "How fast an appliance 'consumes' energy.",
      "misconception": "Thinking Power and Energy are the same; Power is the speed of use, Energy is the total amount used."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy",
      "simpleDefinition": "The total amount of work done over a period of time, measured in Joules (J).",
      "anchor": "The total 'fuel' used up during a task.",
      "misconception": "Confusing Joules (Energy) with Watts (Power)."
    },
    {
      "term": "Frequency",
      "simpleDefinition": "The number of complete cycles an alternating current (AC) makes per second, measured in Hertz (Hz).",
      "anchor": "The 'heartbeat' or rhythm of the electricity.",
      "misconception": "Thinking frequency applies to Direct Current (DC), which does not cycle."
    },
    {
      "term": "Impedance",
      "simpleDefinition": "The total opposition to current flow in an AC circuit, combining resistance and reactance, measured in Ohms (Ω).",
      "anchor": "The 'AC version' of resistance.",
      "misconception": "Thinking impedance only applies to DC circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "Power Factor",
      "simpleDefinition": "A ratio (expressed as a number between 0 and 1) showing how effectively electricity is being used.",
      "anchor": "The efficiency score of a circuit.",
      "misconception": "Trying to assign a unit like Volts or Amps to it; it is a ratio and has no unit."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Quantity is the 'what', Unit is the 'how much'.",
    "Base units are the building blocks; derived units are the recipe.",
    "Resistance is the opposition; Resistivity is the material's property.",
    "Power is the rate; Energy is the total."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using 'Amps' or 'Volts' as the quantity name instead of the unit.",
    "Believing Power and Energy use the same unit.",
    "Confusing Resistance with Resistivity.",
    "Thinking weight and mass are the same unit in SI."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Base and Derived General Units",
      "objective": "Identify the standard SI units for length, mass, time, temperature, area, volume, density, and velocity.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In the electrical trade, precision is everything. We use the SI Units system—the international 'rulebook' for measurement—to ensure every calculation is consistent across the globe. You must distinguish between a 'Quantity' (the physical property, like length) and a 'Unit' (the standard used to measure it, like meters). Using the unit name to describe the quantity is a common beginner mistake; always keep them distinct.",
        "Base Units are the fundamental building blocks of all measurement. For an electrician, the key base units are length (measured in meters, m), mass (measured in kilograms, kg), time (measured in seconds, s), and temperature (measured in Kelvin, K). Note that in technical science, we use kilograms for mass, which is different from weight.",
        "Derived Units are 'recipes' created by combining base units. For example, Area is length multiplied by length, giving us square meters (m²). Volume is cubic meters (m³). Velocity measures how fast something moves in a specific direction, recorded in meters per second (m/s). Finally, Density describes how much mass is packed into a volume, measured in kilograms per cubic meter (kg/m³). Using the correct unit prevents dangerous installation errors, such as miscalculating the cross-sectional area of a cable."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember: Quantity is the 'what' (e.g., Length), and Unit is the 'how much' (e.g., meters)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Electrical Quantities and Units",
      "objective": "Identify the specific SI units for electrical quantities including resistance, power, frequency, current, voltage, and energy.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "When dealing with electrical quantities, the terminology must be exact. We measure the quantity 'Current' in Amperes (A), and 'Voltage' in Volts (V). Resistance is the opposition to current flow, measured in Ohms (Ω). Do not confuse Resistance with Resistivity; while resistance is a circuit's total opposition, resistivity is a property of the material itself. In AC circuits, we use Impedance (Ω) to describe the total opposition, which includes Inductive Reactance (Ω) and Capacitive Reactance (Ω).",
        "Power and Energy are distinct concepts. Power is the rate at which energy is used, measured in Watts (W). Energy is the total amount of work done over time, measured in Joules (J). Think of Power as the speed of consumption and Energy as the total 'fuel' used. For alternating current, we measure Frequency—the number of cycles per second—in Hertz (Hz).",
        "More advanced components involve Inductance, measured in Henrys (H), and Capacitance, measured in Farads (F). Finally, you will encounter Power Factor. This is an efficiency ratio expressed as a number between 0 and 1. Because it is a ratio, it is 'dimensionless,' meaning it has no unit at all. Mastering these units allows you to communicate technical specifications accurately on any job site."
      ],
      "hint": "Watch out for Power vs. Energy; one is the rate (Watts), the other is the total (Joules)."
    }
  ]
}

